Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button (in `EditProductPage.xaml`)

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2. Guard Navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

Override `OnNavigating` with a deferral to show an async confirmation dialog and optionally cancel:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

## 3. ViewModel `CancelCommand`

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating above, which shows the dialog
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**

- `GetDeferral()` is required for async guards — without it the navigation completes before your dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default back-arrow tap, so your command controls what happens (here it just calls `GoToAsync("..")` which re-enters the guard).
